8  COPYING TELEWAR
9
10 TeleWar is not copy protected. It may
11 be copied using any of the regular Amiga
12 copy techniques from your workbench of the
13 CLI. Please read your Amiga manual for
14 the particulars of disk copying should
15 you be unfamiliar with these procedures.
16
17 Before using the program for the first
18 time, we recommend that you make a
19 working copy of TeleWar. Please rename
20 the copy TeleWar_WB, just like the
21 master program disk.
22
23 If you have more than 512K of RAM in
24 your Amiga, it is also possible to copy
25 TeleWar graphics and telecommunication
26 files over to the Ramdisk for very quick
27 file access. Use the copy icons provided
28 in the Tele_Batch directory/drawer on
29 the TeleWar_WB disk (See Appendix A).
30
31 If you are interested in putting TeleWAr
32 on a hard disk see Appendix C.
33
34 We have offered you TeleWar without copy
35 protection and at a reasonable price
36 (without high price packaging), because
37 that is what you have requested. By
38 honoring our Copyright and preventing
39 unauthorized distribution you can show
40 us that lack of hard copy protection on
41 TeleWar was a wise choice.
42
43

                  Page 5


1  LOADING
2
3  To play TeleWar you will need:
4
5  + An Amiga Computer 500, 1000, or 2000
6  + 512K or more of RAM
7  + An "AT" command set compatable modem
8    operating at 9600, 2400, 1200, or 300
9    baud.
10
11 512K RAM Amiga
12
13 Follow the regular startup instructions
14 for your Amiga (using Kickstart 1.2, if
15 you have the 1000). When the Amiga
16 requests the 1.2 Workbench Disk, insert
17 the TeleWar_WB working copy into the
18 internal drive. TeleWar will autoboot.
19
20 Note: With 1 external drive mounted to a
21 512K Amiga, TeleWar requires ALL the
22 memory to operate. Even WorkBench cannot
23 be loaded, let alone another multitask.
24 It also will not load if two external
25 drives are mounted with only 512K RAM.
26 
27 AN Amiga with 1 meg or more of RAM
28
29 Boot up with your favorite WorkBench
30 disk as usual. Place the TeleWar_WB
31 disk in any drive and double click on
32 the TeleWar_WB disk icon to open the
33 TeleWar window.
34
35 Finally, double click on the TeleWar
36 program icon to load the program.
37
38 TeleWar is a "smart" program and will
39 find itself and its file directories,
40 whether it resides on the RAMDISK, or
41 floppy drives df0:, df1:, df2:, or df3:.
42
43

                 Page 6


1  If your 1 meg Amiga has only one floppy
2  disk drive, and you want to load TeleWar
3  from your favorite WorkBench disk, you
4  must click on the One_Drive icon first,
5  before starting TeleWar. This sets the
6  assigns correctly to the TeleWar_WB disk
7  so that AmigaDOS does not get confused.
8
9
10 When the Program Begins
11
12 After a few moments, the TeleWar credits
13 screen will be displayed on your
14 monitor, indicating that the program
15 has correctly loaded. To leave the
16 credits screen and play TeleWar, click
17 the left mouse button. A requestor will
18 ask you for a manual validation
19 character. After you find and type this
20 letter, TeleWar will load in the River
21 Meadow Terrain Map. You are now ready to
22 begin.
23
24 BASIC OPERATION
25
26 Mouse
27
28 TeleWar uses the familiar Intuition
29 user interface. You interact with
30 TeleWar by means of the mouse, which is
31 used to move the mouse pointer across
32 the screen. The left mouse button allows
33 you to select and move game pieces,
34 and make requester and control panel
35 gadget selections. The right mouse
36 button displays and selects menu options
37 that control program operations.
38
39 WHEN TELECONNECTED, DON'T UNNECESSARILY
40 HOLD DOWN THE RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON, AS IT
41 WILL PREVENT SERIAL READS AND CAUSE YOUR
42 AMIGA TO MISS YOUR OPPONENT'S MOVES, AND
43 DISRUPT THE GAME!

                 Page 7


1  Keyboard
2 
3  The keyboard is used to input specific
4  modem and opponent telecommunication
5  parameters, file names, and messages
6  (once a teleconnection is established).
7
8  Messages may be typed at any time during
9  a game. Because of the intensive time
10 requirements of TeleWar piece animation,
11 however, keyboard input will be ignored
12 while a piece is moving across the
13 screen. This will not effect the player
14 whose turn is current, but it may cause
15 the other waiting player to develop a
16 type-between-the-moves typing style. We
17 apologize for this inconvenience, but
18 feel that it is necessary to insure
19 error free transmissions and receptions
20 of game moves.
21
22 Verification Requesters
23
24 A verification requester will appear in
25 the center of your Control Panel (and
26 in the center on the disk I/O screen)
27 whenever you request an action that may
28 drastically effect the current game
29 configuration. Moving the mouse pointer
30 within the borders of these requesters
31 and clicking the left mouse button will
32 generally cause the requested action to
33 be initiated, while moving the mouse
34 pointer outside the requester and
35 clicking the left mouse button will
36 cancel the requested action. These
37 requesters are designed to protect you
38 from accidentally initiating an action.
39 Please read these requesters carefully
40 before clicking the left mouse button,
41 otherwise you may initiate an action
42 that you do not expect.
43

                 Page 8

1  A TELEWAR OVERVIEW
2
3  TeleWar allows two Amiga users with
4  modems to play an animated strategy war
5  game over the telephone. Two players may
6  also play on a single computer.
7
8  TeleWar offers 3 perspectively viewed
9  battlefield maps  --  River Meadow,
10 Marshland Bog, and Desert Dunes  --  upon
11 which to battle your opponent.
12
13 The fully animated TeleWar attack pieces
14 represent four types of military
15 armament. In addition, animated supply
16 vehicle are provided, as well as
17 animated air support.
18
19 Pieces move, turn. and fire on command.
20 Simply point the mouse to a game unit on
21 the upper portion of the screen or to
22 one of the positions marked on the
23 Tactical Grid, and click the left
24 button. The chosen piece is now marked
25 by a yellow bracket. To move the unit
26 just point to another location on the
27 upper screen and press the left mouse
28 button. To fire this unit, click on the
29 FIRE gadget. It's simple and easy.
30
31 One player blasts away until each piece
32 has moved and fired once, then clicks
33 the PASS gadget to pass the play to his
34 opponent. Each time a piece is hit it
35 sustains damage. Two much damage, and
36 the piece is destroyed. Destroyed
37 pieces may be obliterated by a hit from
38 either side.
39
40 The goal of the game is to destroy the
41 enemy HeadQuarters -- not an easy task!
42 First you must find a way through the
43 formidable defenses of your opponent!

                 Page 9

1  THE TELEWAR DISPLAY
2
3  The TeleWar display is divided into two
4  primary sections. The upper half portion
5  of the display is called the Battlefield
6  Terrain Map View Window, while the lower
7  half of the display is called the
8  Control Panel.
9
10
11 Battlefield Terrain Map
12
13 The Battlefield Terrain Map View Window
14 displays a close up perspective view of
15 the TeleWar Battlefield and the
16 positioned military ordnance of both the
17 Blue and the Red armies. At any given 
18 time one-sixth of entire Battlefield
19 area, depicted in full on the Tactical
20 Grid (see below), is visible.
21
22 Movement and attacks by army units are
23 animated in the Battlefield Terrain Map.
24 Generally, only those areas of the map
25 containing a player's Ordnance unit can
26 be viewed. Calling Air Support, however
27 will scroll across the one-third portion
28 of the map over which Air Support flies.
29
30 The Control Panel
31
32 The LOWER half of the TeleWar display is
33 the Control Panel. The Control Panel is
34 comprised of five distinct areas,
35 providing information, game control, and
36 user to user interface, referred to as
37 follows:
38
39       + The Menu/Message Bar
40       + The Ordnance Status Table
41       + The Tactical Grid
42       + Ordnance Control Gadgets
43       + The Chat lines -- RECV & SEND

                 Page 10

1  The Menu/Message
2
3  The black bar at the top of the Control
4  Panel is the Menu and Message bar. Don't
5  let it's location fool you. This is the
6  same Intuition menu bar that usually
7  sits atop your WorkBench Screen. The
8  Menus will be displayed whenever the
9  right mouse button is depressed. See the
10 section on Menus to learn the purpose of
11 each.
12
13 During the coarse of a game, the Menu
14 Bar will display MESSAGES to you, the
15 Commanding officer, from your field
16 units. If you are in doubt as to the
17 result of your current action, read the
18 message bar. For instance, if you have
19 just fired on an enemy unit, your
20 "troops" will inform you whether
21 you hit the enemy or not.
22
23 ORDNANCE STATUS TABLE
24 
25 The left third portion of the Control
26 Panel displays the Ordnance Status
27 Table. The status of the currently
28 selected military ordnance will always
29 be displayed on the table. Whether a
30 unit has the necessary fuel, ammo, or
31 defensive stamina to complete a mission
32 can be determined from the table.
33
34 Above the Ordnance Status Table the name
35 of the army, whose turn is current, is
36 displayed. The two armies are known as
37 the RED and BLUE. Please note that
38 these names are not meant to represent
39 any actual forces in the world today.
40 Rather think of them as designators as
41 might be placed on the two opposing
42 sides in an actual military war game.
43

                  Page 11

1  Ordnance Status Table displays the
2  following data:
3
4  Ordnance Type -- type of military unit
5  selected, either Light Artillery, Light
6  Armor, Heavy Armor, Heavy artillery,
7  Supply Vehicle, Air Support Transmitter,
8  or HeadQuarters.
9
10 Position -- the horizontal and vertical
11 coordinates of the selected unit on the
12 Tactical Grid Map that is divided into a
13 32 (horz.) x 20 (vert.) grid work.
14
15 Ammo -- amount of ammunition remaining,
16 where 1 Ammo + 1 firing by that unit.
17
18 Gun Range -- the maximum horizontal gun
19 range for that unit, where 1 unit + 1
20 square on the 32x20 Tactical Grid Map.
21 The maximum vertical and diagonal range
22 is that which is visible on at any time
23 on the Battlefield Terrain Map Window.
24
25 Defense -- the current defense against
26 destruction for the selected unit (hit
27 points remaining), where 0 = destroyed.
28
29 Fuel -- amount of fuel remaining, where
30 1 Fuel unit will move the ordnance 1
31 square on the 32x20 Tactical Grid Map.
32
33 Gun Power -- the amount of damage
34 subtracted from the target enemy unit
35 defense stat with each successful hit by
36 this ordnance type.
37
38 Mobility -- the maximum mobility range
39 for the selected unit, where 1 mobility
40 unit will move the ordnance 1 square on
41 the 32x20 Tactical Grid Map.
42
43

                Page 12


1  TACTICAL GRID MAP
2
3  The display in the middle third of the
4  Control Panel is the Tactical Grid Map.
5  In turn, each of the three Battlefield
6  Maps of TeleWar will be herein displayed
7  in miniature under a 32x20 grid overlay.
8 
9  All Prominent BattleField Terrain Map
10 features, such as roads, rivers, lakes,
11 and bridges are depicted in miniature on
12 the Tactical Grid Map.
13
14 The Terrain Grid Map also displays the
15 positions of the Army whose turn is
16 current, as well as the last known
17 positions of previously detected enemy
18 units.  In order for those positions to
19 be updated, a player must select a
20 friendly unit in the vicinity.  Position
21 updates only occur when the map area in
22 question is displayed in the upper
23 screen.  If a player no longer has any
24 units in that vicinity, then it is not
25 possible to view that area without
26 calling Air Support.
27
28 Position updates for an entire one third
29 of the map over which your plane flies
30 is received after Air Support is called.
31 Note that the surviving crew from
32 destroyed units that are still displayed
33 as debris, can send in position updates.
34 Once these units have been obliterated,
35 however, this is no longer possible.
36
37 The current unit chosen for action will
38 blink on the Tactical Grid Map.  Another
39 friendly unit may be chosen for action
40 by clicking on one of the colored
41 squares from the Tactical Grid Map.  Red
42 squares indicate the RED ARMY units, and
43 Yellow squares indicate BLUE ARMY units.

                  Page 13


1  UNIT COMMAND GADGETS
2
3  The right third portion of the Control
4  Panel contains the Command Gadgets,
5  separated into four clusters.  When an
6  activity gadget is still active for a
7  given unit, it is RED.  Activity gadgets
8  are MOVE, FIRE, SUPPLY,  and AIR SUPPORT.
9  Choice gadgets are either BLUE (current
10 setting) or WHITE (not chose).
11
12 Firing Direction Cluster
13
14 The Firing Direction Gadget Cluster
15 chooses and indicates the firing angle
16 for the currently selected unit.  Eight
17 compass oriented firing angles are
18 available.  The selected unit Battlefield
19 Map image will graphically reflect the
20 chosen firing direction.
21
22 Primary Command Gadget Cluster
23
24 The Primary Command Cluster contains the
25 MOVE, PASS, and FIRE gadgets, as well as
26 forward and backward unit selection
27 gadgets.  The << and >> gadgets will page
28 backwards or forwards through the Army's
29 remaining units on the battlefield.
30
31 FIRE must be clicked on to Fire the
32 selected unit in the direction indicated
33 in  BLUE on the Firing Direction Cluster.
34
35 PASS should be clicked on when the
36 player has finished commanding his units
37 and is ready to pass the turn -- and
38 game control -- to his opponent.
39 
40 MOVE is primarily just an indicated as
41 to whether the current selected unit has
42 yet moved.  Moves are made in the upper
43 Battlefield Map View Window.

               Page 14

1  Supply Gadget Cluster
2
3  A unit may be supplied with FUEL or AMMO
4  once during a single turn.  In order for
5  SUPPLY to occur, a supply truck must be
6  adjacent (North, South, East, West) to
7  the vehicle requesting SUPPLY.  The
8  player must select FUEL or AMMO to be
9  supplied by clicking on either of these
10 gadgets.  Then click on the Supply gadget
11 to initiate the transfer.  SUPPLY will
12 bring the selected unit up to its
13 maximum quantity of fuel or ammunition.
14
15 Supply trucks cannot be resupplied by
16 another supply truck, but must go back
17 to HeadQuarters to be refueled.
18
19 ”Air Support Gadget Cluster•
20
21 The Air Support Gadget Cluster is used
22 to call and control the flight path of
23 an air attack on the enemy.  If the
24 player's Transmitter has not been
25 destroyed, AIR SUPPORT can be called;
26 and only as long as less than 5 units
27 have moved and 5 units have fired.  At
28 the fifth move or firing, Air Support is
29 deactivated for the rest of that turn.
30
31 The TOP, MID, and LOW gadgets choose the
32 portion of the map over which Air
33 Support will fly.  The plane will then
34 randomly strafe one of seven horizontal
35 grid rows within that 1/3 map portion,
36 inflicting 5 points of damage on any
37 enemy units in its path.  Note that
38 friendly units are not so damaged.
39
40 A player's turn automatically ends after
41 Air Support has completed a strafing run
42 on the enemy and has radioed back the
43 updated enemy unit positions.

                 Page 15


ÜjÜŒ





1  ”RECV AND SEND MESSAGE LINES•
2
3  The RECV and SEND message lines at the
4  bottom of the TeleWar screen are only
5  active after a teleconnection has been
6  established.
7
8  During game play, letters typed  on the
9  keyboard will be displayed on the SEND
10 line.  The SEND Message line will allow
11 all the normal line editing control of
12 the Amiga keyboard: cursor keys, back
13 space, and the DEL key.  The message
14 text will be transmitted either when you
15 hit RETURN, or when you have typed to
16 the end of the SEND message line.
17
18 The RECV message line will display the
19 text message that is received from the
20 teleconnected computer of your opponent.
21 A chime will sound when an incoming
22 message is displayed to alert you to the
23 RECV message.  With some modems the RECV
24 line will echo your SEND message should
25 the teleconnection be broken or lost.
26
27 ”ORDNANCE © The Game Pieces•
28
29 There are seven different game unit
30 markers in TeleWar that are placed on
31 the Battlefield Map at the start of a
32 game.  Each of the three Battlefield Maps
33 offers four game piece scenarios (see
34 the Scenario Menu ) that provide various
35 unit configurations and placement.
36
37 Each Ordnance type has a different
38 amount of FUEL, AMMO, DEFENSE ability,
39 MOBILITY, GUN RANGE  and GUN POWER. It is
40 important that the players use the
41 ordnance types effectively, together and
42 alone, during the course of a game in
43 order to maximize their effectiveness.

                  Page 16


ÜjÜŒ





1  ”HeadQuarters•
2
3  The HeadQuarter (HQ) for each Army is
4  designated by a flagged tent.  HQ is a
5  stationary object, and cannot fire on
6  the enemy.  It's sole protection is the
7  other ordnance units, who can defend it.
8
9  A game is won when a player manages to
10 destroy his opponents HQ.  Conversely, it
11 is important for a player to protect his
12 HQ in order to prevent his opponent from
13 winning the game.
14
15 ”Transmitter•
16
17 The Transmitter is also a stationary
18 object that cannot defend itself.  Its
19 sole purpose in TeleWar is to call Air
20 Support for a strafing run against the
21 enemy.  Once a player's Transmitter has
22 been destroyed, he can no longer call
23 for Air Support.  Therefore, it is
24 important for each player to protect his
25 own Transmitter, while attempting to
26 destroy his opponent's Transmitter.
27
28 ”Light Artillery•
29
30 Light Artillery in TeleWar is depicted
31 as a jeep with a mounted, short range
32 RPG.  The Light Artillery units have the
33 longest MOBILITY range and the largest
34 FUEL and AMMO supply of any of the
35 combat units.  conversely, they also
36 have the lowest GUN POWER, GUN RANGE, 
37 and DEFENSE against enemy fire.
38
39 Light Artillery can easily be the first
40 to attack, but without heavy unit
41 support, will probably be the first to
42 be destroyed.  Nevertheless, when used
43 together, they can produce enough fire

                  Page 17


ÜjÜŒ





1  power to take out an enemy unit.
2 
3  They are also a good choice for clearing
4  away the debris of destroyed units,
5  thereby leaving the fire power of heavy
6  units for attacking active enemy units
7  otherwise shielded by the debris.
8
9  ”Light Armor•
10
11 The Light Armor in TeleWar is depicted
12 as a single-barrel light tank.  They
13 carry a respectable quantity of FUEL,
14 have a good MOBILITY range, GUN RANGE
15 and GUN POWER.  They proved good backup
16 support for the Light Artillery, and do
17 not need frequent refueling.  They are
18 also effective when used with heavier
19 units to take out any enemy unit.
20
21 ”Heavy Armor•
22
23 The Heavy Armor in TeleWar is depicted
24 as a two-barrel tank.  These units have a
25 very high DEFENSE rating, a GUN RANGE
26 that encompasses the entire BattleField
27 Map View Window, and a high GUN POWER.
28 They can easily fire upon enemy Light
29 Artillery and Armor units, while staying
30 out of range of return fire.
31
32 Such power, however, means that they
33 have a short MOBILITY range, and carry a
34 small FUEL and AMMO supply.
35
36 ”Heavy Artillery•
37
38 Heavy Artillery should be considered
39 Heavy Armored Artillery.  In TeleWar
40 they are depicted as the large gun on a
41 tread.  The highest DEFENSE, GUN RANGE,
42 and GUN POWER make this the most
43 devastating of pieces.  Mobility, FUEL

                 Page 18


ÜjÜŒ





1  and AMMO are all very low, requiring
2  constant resupply as this unit is moved
3  across the Battlefield Map.  Once it is
4  in position, however, little can stand
5  for long against its mighty fire power.
6
7  It's extremely long GUN RANGE can be used
8  effectively for defense along the right
9  and left borders fo the map, where they
10 can see & fire farther than any and all
11 approaching enemy units.
12
13 ”Supply Vehicles•
14
15 Supply Vehicles in TeleWar are depicted
16 as trucks.  Supply Vehicles cannot FIRE
17 on enemy units, but do have a huge FUEL
18 and MOBILITY range.  Their sole purpose
19 is to shuttle FUEL and AMMO to the
20 combat units in the field.  Because of
21 the low DEFENSE  rating of Supply
22 Vehicles, it is important to keep them
23 out of range of enemy fire.
24
25 They have immense strategic importance.
26 An offensive thrust at the enemy without
27 an accompanying Supply Vehicle will
28 usually fizzle as combat units run out
29 of FUEL and AMMO.   On the other hand,
30 the player who destroys his opponent's
31 Supply Vehicles has almost certainly won
32 the game.
33
34 Supply Vehicles, like combat units, can
35 run out of FUEL.  But Supply Vehicles,
36 however, can only be refueled at HQ.  A
37 player who lets a truck get too low on
38 FUEL to get back to HQ, has all but
39 removed that piece from the game.  Of
40 course it is still possible to bring
41 combat units to the Supply vehicle for
42 resupply.
43

                  Page 19


ÜjÜŒ





1  ”STARTING TELEWAR•
2
3  Start TeleWar by choosing the START A
4  GAME menu selection under the PLAY menu.
5  TeleWar will proceed to load in the
6  Terrain Map data file, and then place
7  the military ordnance game pieces in
8  their initial positions.  The side that
9  is currently chosen under the PLAY menu
10 always begins by taking the first turn.
11
12 Once the game has begun, the positions
13 of all friendly units are displayed on
14 the Tactical Grid Map.  The current unit
15 -- at game start, HeadQuarters -- will be
16 marked by a yellow surrounding bracket
17 in the Battlefield Map View Window,  and
18 will blink its location on the Tactical
19 Grid Map.
20
21 Note that for non-combatant unit (HQ
22 and the Transmitter) the Firing Gadget
23 Direction Cluster disappears, and only 
24 the AIR SUPPORT gadget is activated RED.
25
26 To select another unit as the current
27 unit, point the mouse cursor at any
28 unit visible in the upper Battlefield
29 Map View Window and click the left mouse
30 button.  The Battlefield Map view then
31 realigns itself to the new selected
32 piece, centering it in the display
33 whenever possible.  The Ordnance Status
34 table now displays the data for that
35 unit, and the Command Gadgets reflect
36 your remaining options for that unit.
37
38 Another unit, especially those not in
39 view in the Battlefield Map view window,
40 can also be chosen by clicking the mouse
41 cursor on a friendly colored unit that
42 is marked in RED or YELLOW on the
43 Tactical Grid Map

               Page 20


ÜjÜŒ





1  ”MOVEMENT•
2
3  The selected unit within the yellow
4  bracket can be ordered to move by simply
5  pointing to the desired destination in
6  the Battlefield Map View Window, and
7  clicking the left mouse button.  If the
8  destination is not impassable (occupied
9  by trees, water, another unit, etc.) and
10 is within the movement range of that
11 unit, then the unit will do its best to
12 move to the selected location, avoiding
13 impassable obstructions as it does so.
14
15 Generally, TeleWar determines the best
16 and shortest possible path for a given
17 move (drivers do make mistakes!),
18 taking into consideration the type of
19 terrain, the mobility of the unit, and
20 the FUEL remaining.  The unit may not
21 actually reach the destination, however,
22 because of hills, sand, or bridges that
23 slow the unit's progress, or because the
24 destination was out of the MOBILITY 
25 range of the unit.
26
27 Generally, movement orders that are
28 within the MOBILITY range of a unit are
29 more likely to be accomplished.  Pushing
30 troops beyond their limits can be
31 counter productive.
32
33 Water is always impossible to cross,
34 unless a sand bar is present.  Sand,
35 hills, and sand dues are passable, but
36 do cause delays.  Where such terrains
37 must be crossed, it might be necessary
38 to order a unit to move beyond the
39 destination and/or its MOBILITY range in
40 the hopes that it pushes harder and
41 reaches the actual correct coordinates.
42 The outcome of such moves is variable
43 with the terrain being crossed.

                 Page 21


ÜjÜŒ





1  ”FIRING a UNIT•
2
3  Each unit may FIRE once per turn.  The
4  firing angle is set by clicking on one
5  of eight directions in the Firing Gadget
6  Cluster.  Clicking on the FIRE gadget
7  will cause the selected unit to fire in
8  the direction indicated on the Firing
9  Gadget Cluster.
10
11 When a unit is fired, the shell
12 continues in a straight path until it
13 either (1) hits the first enemy unit it
14 encounters, (2) reaches the end of the
15 GUN RANGE for that unit, or (3) reaches
16 the boundaries of the Battlefield Map
17 view window, at which point it explodes.
18
19 Note that it is sometimes possible to
20 hit an enemy unit not visible (just off
21 screen), but whose coordinates are
22 technically on screen.  Friendly units
23 are never damaged by friendly fire (give
24 these troops SOME credit!).
25
26 A unit hit by enemy fire sustains damage
27 until it is destroyed and reduced to a
28 pile of debris.  Keep in mind that debris
29 can form an effective shield to other
30 units, as the attacking army must waste
31 a shot to clear the debris from the
32 field so that other units can fire at
33 the enemy.  While it is true that an Army
34 can only "hit" enemy units, both sides
35 can obliterate debris from either color
36 army with a single, on target shot.
37
38 The victor of most games is he who best
39 makes use of his fire power during the
40 coarse of a game. Remember the DEFENSE
41 stats of each enemy piece. Don't waste a
42 Heavy artillery shot on an enemy with a
43 Defense of 1, unless it can't be helped.

                Page 22



1  ”PLAYING TELEWAR•
2
3  When Telewar is teleconnected to another
4  computer, every correct move made on one
5  computer is echoed on the other.  The one
6  exception to this is that the receiving
7  computer does not receive the opponent's
8  Tactical Grid Map.
9
10 At the start of a game expect it to take
11 a few minutes for your opponent to make
12 his moves.  Use this time wisely by
13 reading the stats on the enemy units
14 (call it Intelligence Reports), and
15 marking the weaker pieces as good
16 targets.  As the game progresses and
17 units are destroyed, each player will 
18 take less time for a turn.
19
20 Air Support can be called on any turn,
21 as long as (1) the Transmitter is not
22 destroyed, (2) less than 5 units have fired.
24 Air support is very powerful, and can
25 quickly reduce the enemy's strength.  But
26 called too frequently, gives your
27 opponent the opportunity to position a
28 large number of forces for a major
29 offensive against your HeadQuarters or
30 transmitter.  Relying solely on Air
31 Support rarely wins at TeleWar.
32
33 On the other hand, however, Air Support
34 might just pull out a victory for an
35 otherwise losing player, if frequently
36 used at the end of a game.
37
38 ”ENDING a TELEWAR•
39
40 One player must choose the End/Cede Game
41 menu option, after a player's HA has
42 been destroyed, before another game can
43 begin.

                     Page 23


1  MENUS
2
3  Menus headings are displayed when the
4  right mouse button is depressed.  By
5  moving the mouse cursor over these menu
6  headings, the menu items under each
7  heading will be displayed.  Moving the
8  cursor down the menu item list will
9  highlight that item.  Releasing the right
10 menu button while a menu item is
11 highlighted will activate that menu
12 selection.
13
14 When a menu item is selected, it may
15 cause other menu items to be activated
16 or deactivated (ghosted).  Ghosted menu
17 items cannot be selected.
18
19 When teleconnected, the menus are always
20 accessible to the player whose turn is
21 current.  However the menus are not
22 available to the receiving player.  The
23 reason for this is that when the right
24 menu button is depressed, Intuition
25 interrupts all computer activity.  This
26 means that the Amiga is not checking
27 the serial port for incoming moves from
28 the teleconnected computer.  Moves may
29 not be received, thus resulting in
30 mismatched unit positions.  For this same
31 reason it is important that you do not
32 hold the right menu button down during
33 game play, as the interrupt will still
34 be generated that prevents serial reads.
35
36 Should you need to get at the menu bar
37 when it is off, simply point to the
38 message bar and click the left mouse
39 button.  A requester will ask you to
40 verify the request.  Be warned however,
41 that activating the menu bar (or even
42 the requester) may result in a missed
43 moved from the other computer, thereby

                 Page 24


1  requiring that the game by saved,
2  reloaded, transmitted, and re-started.
3
4  It is recommended that you type a 
5  message to your opponent requesting that
6  he stop moving for a couple of minutes,
7  while you access the menu.  This will be
8  necessary, for instance, should you wish
9  to save a game in progress.  Once menu
10 activity has been completed, you can
11 then type him a message to recommence
12 troop movement.  It is advisable that, if
13 possible, you only access menus during
14 your turn -- and then infrequently.
15
16 ”TeleWar Menu•
