                      Page 36


1  ”Teleconnect Procedures•
2
3  The primary purpose of TeleWar is to
4  allow people to play an animated
5  strategy war game over the telephone,
6  using a computer and a modem.
7
8  Up until now, modems have been used
9  primarily for contacting bulletin boards
10 that allow the user to post messages and
11 access download files. While it has
12 always been possible for most users to
13 establish a direct teleconnection with
14 other computerists, it is rarely done
15 because of lack of familiarity with
16 modem protocols and software.
17
18 TeleWar gives telecomputerists another
19 use for their modems, allowing them to
20 play games with another human being.
21 The mystique of telecommunications is
22 gone. All with which you the user must
23 be concerned, is playing the game.
24 TeleWar will handle the rest.
25
26 ”Setting Modem Parameters•
27
28 In order for TeleWar to work correctly,
29 it is necessary that it be able to
30 communicate with your modem and with the
31 modem of your opponent. A few simple
32 settings must be input to TeleWar so
33 that the computer may communicate
34 coherently with your modem. These
35 settings need be made but once, and then
36 saved to the disk. Thereafter, whenever
37 TeleWar is loaded, these settings will
38 be loaded with it.
39
40 In order to set your modem parameters
41 you should select the Modem Parameter
42 option in the Tele Files menu (page 16 
43 describes the Tele Files menu).

                   Page 37


1  Baud Rate
2
3  Baud rate is the number of binary digits
4  per second transmitted across your
5  modem. Most modems today commonly
6  transmit at 300, 1200, or 2400 baud.
7  TeleWar supports all these baud rates,
8  as well as the new 9600 baud modems.
9
10 Set the baud rate to a level that is
11 supported by your modem, and that you
12 will most commonly be using. The higher
13 baud rates will transmit data more
14 quickly, so they are preferred.
15
16 Dial and Answer Commands
17
18 Modems recognize a command instruction
19 set that allows the computer to direct
20 the modem to perform certain activities,
21 like dialing and answering the phone.
22 TeleWar supports the "AT" command set
23 standard.
24
25 If your phone is touch tone, click on
26 ATDT; or if your phone is a pulse rotary
27 phone, click on ATDP to set the Dial
28 Commands. If your modem recognizes a 
29 different command string,  or if
30 you wish to use additional commands in
31 the dialing command string, click on the
32 custom dialing command input box and
33 type in your dialing command string.
34 
35 Answer Commands should be set in the
36 same manner. ATSO=1 will answer your 
37 phone after one ring, while ATA will
38 pick up the phone as soon as you enter
39 the Answer mode. Custom answer command
40 strings may also be input.
41
42 After the Modem Parameter have been
43 set, be sure to save them to the disk.

                 Page 38


1  Setting Opponent Parameters
2
3  The next step necessary is to input the
4  opponent parameters. These are set by
5  selecting the Opponent Parameters option
6  in the Tele Files menu (see page 16 for
7  a description of the Tele Files menu).
8
9  Type in the telephone number and the
10 selected baud rate at which you will be
11 playing that opponent. The baud rate
12 should be the highest one common to both
13 your modems. Then type the opponents
14 name into the File Name box and SAVE the
15 Opponent file. The next time that you
16 wish to play TeleWar with that opponent
17 you need only load the Opponent
18 Parameter file from the disk.
19
20 Before you establish a teleconnection,
21 whether you are Sending or Receiving,
22 you MUST set the Opponent Parameters or
23 load an Opponent Parameter File.
24
25 Voice Contact
26
27 It is recommended that telephone voice
28 contact first be established between the
29 TeleWar players to verify who will enter
30 the Sending mode and dial the opponent,
31 and who will enter Receiving mode and
32 answer the call. The caller should
33 enter Sending Mode, and the Receiver
34 should enter Receiving mode, if ATSO=1
35 is the default.
36
37 When both computers are ready to go, the
38 players can agree to initiate contact in
39 15 seconds after voice connection is
40 broken. This will minimize the chance
41 of an extraneous incoming call ringing
42 the telephone before the Sending
43 computer can Dial the Number.

                   Page 39

1  Teleconnect Procedure Summary
2
3  1. Each computer should load TeleWar.
4
5  2. Set your Modem Parameters (if not
6     already set).
7
8  3. Load the Opponent Parameters for your
9     chosen opponent.
10
11 4. Call your opponent (voice) to decide
12    who will call whom.
13
14 5. Be sure that both computers are in
15    the same Map and that a game
16    has not already been started.
17
18 6. While still voice connected, the
19    caller should enter the Sending Mode
20    and the one whom will answer should
21    enter the Receiving mode (if ATSO=1
22    answer command is set).
23
24 7. Hang up the phone (voice).
25
26 8. The Sending computer chooses the
27    Dial the Number menu option, and the
28    computer dials the telephone number
29    and waits for a connection.
30
31 9. If ATSO=1 answer command is set, the
32    Receiving computer will answer the
33    telephone and make the connection.
34
35 10. If ATA answer command is set on the
36     Receiving computer, that player
37     should enter Receiving mode upon
38     hearing the telephone ring.
39
40 11. The Teleconnection is established.
41     Players may now type messages on
42     their keyboards, Start a New Game,
43     Load, Transmit & Play a saved game.

                 Page 40


1  TELECONNECT © Another Method
2
3  Some non-standard modems that do not
4  Answer the phone or recognize the "AT"
5  command set may not initially seem to
6  work with TeleWar. But don't give up
7  hope yet! You can still play TeleWar
8  over the phone by using the NULL MODEM
9  CONNECT menu option.
10
11 Just try the following procedure to
12 attempt to establish a teleconnection.
13
14 Use a telecomm software package that
15 does work with your modem to establish a
16 teleconnection with a terminal software
17 package on another computer.
18
19 If you are using another terminal
20 software package it should be set to the
21 following telecomm specifications.
22
23       Baud Rate      -- your baud rate
24       Parity         -- NONE
25       Data length    -- 8 bits
26       Stop bits      -- 1 stop bit
27       Duplex         -- Full Duplex
28
29 After a connection is made, close the
30 other telecomm program. The telephone
31 line connection should remain open.
32
33 Now load in TeleWar. Both computers
34 should immediately be placed in the NULL
35 MODEM CONNECT mode. Do not do anything
36 else until you have alowed enough time
37 to pass for the other player to have put
38 his computer into NULL MODEM CONNECT
39 mode.
40
41 Finally, a player should type a message
42 to determine if the teleconnection was
43 successfully established.

                   Page 41


1  USING THE RAMDISK
2
3  If you have more than 512K of RAM on
4  your Amiga, you may want to copy the
5  TeleWar graphics and data files over to
6  the RAMDISK before loading TeleWar.
7
8  An iconed program in the TeleWar_Batch
9  drawer called DiskToRam will copy the
10 appropriate files to the Ramdisk, making
11 all the appropriate assigns so that
12 TeleWar knows where to find the files.
13
14 If you do use TeleWar from the Ramdisk
15 and have saved any opponent parameters
16 files or saved any games, the Tele_Files
17 directory and files must be copied back
18 to your TeleWar_WB floppy disk. Use the
19 RamToDisk icon driven program (in the
20 Tele_Batch drawer) to copy the
21 Tele_Files back to the program disk
22 before you turn off your computer.
23
24 If this is not done, then any Tele_Files
25 created during this session will be
26 lost! When RamToDisk is run, it also
27 cleans up after itself by removing all
28 the TeleWar files from the Ramdisk so
29 that the space can be used be other
30 applications.
31
32 Improved Operation
33
34 While TeleWar works great in a 512K
35 Amiga, it works even better in an Amiga
36 equipped with a Fast RAM expansion.
37 TeleWar was written to take full
38 advantage of Fast RAM's increased
39 program execution speed. With Fast RAM
40 the TeleWAr program code can operate
41 without sharing processor time while
42 displaying the graphics or playing
43 digitised sound.

                   Page 42


1  TELEWAR DIRECTORIES
2
3  TeleWar accesses two main directories
4  during program operation.
5
6  Tele War Directory
7
8  The Tele_War directory contains all of
9  the graphics and sound data files
10 necessary to the program. Placing these
11 files on the Ramdisk will significantly
12 increase load speeds during the coarse
13 of the game. The Tele_War directory is
14 assigned the logical device name War: so
15 that it may be found by the program
16 whether it resides on a floppy, a hard
17 disk, or on the Ramdisk.
18
19 Tele Files Directory
20
21 The Tele_Files directory contains all of
22 the user accessed I/O files.
23
24 The modemset file contains the default
25 baud rate and both the call and answer
26 command strings settings for your modem.
27
28 The TeleFiles subdirectory contains the
29 Opponent Parameter files of baud rates
30 and telephone numbers of your opponents.
31 
32 The GameFiles subdirectory contains the
33 TeleWar saved game files for each
34 Battlefield Map. Saved games for River
35 Meadow map are identified by the "R"
36 prefix, Marshland Bog saved games are
37 identified by the "M" prefix, and Desert
38 Dunes saved games are identified by the
39 "D" prefix.
40
41 The Tele_Files directory is assigned the
42 logical device name Tele+Files: so that
43 ot may be found by the program whether

                   Page 43


1  it resides on a floppy, a hard disk, or
2  on the Ramdisk.
3
4  If you have both TeleWar and TeleGames
5  (Chess, Checkers, and Backgammon) on
6  your hard disk, you will need only one
7  tele_files directory. The files from
8  both games are totally compatable. The
9  same modemset file will work for both
10 programs, the opponent files will load
11 into both programs, and the saved game 
12 files will safely exist side by side
13 with one another.
14
15
16 USING TELEWAR FROM A HARD DISK
17
18 To use TeleWar from your hard disk first
19 copy TeleWar and the TeleWar.info icon
20 file to our hard drive in any directory
21 level you like. Next copy Tele_War
22 and Tele_Files directories over to your
23 hard disk.
24
25 On order for TeleWar to locate these 
26 directories, you will need to add the
27 War: and Tele+Files: assigns to your
28 s/startup-sequence. The assigns are as
29 follows:
30
31 Assign War:
32 <hard drive>:<directory path>/Tele_War
33
34 Assign Tele+Files:
35 <hard drive>:<directory path>/Tele_Files
36
37 where <hard drive> = dh0:, dh2:, etc.,
38 and <directory path> = directory
39
40 If this is unclear, just take a look at
41 the TeleWar s/startup-sequence for an
42 example on how the assigns should be
43 made.

                    Page 44



1               Trouble Shooting
2
3  TeleWar will not Load
4
5  1) Check to see that enough memory is
6     available for TeleWar.
7  2) On a 512K Amiga only 1 external drive
8     may be connected, and no other tasks
9     should be running.
10 3) Check to see that TeleWar_WB
11    working copy is not damaged.
12
13
14 TeleWar will not dial a Number
15
16 1) Is your modem powered & connected?
17 2) Check that the modem parameters are
18    correctly set.
19 3) Is your modem "AT" command set
20    compatable?
21 3) Consult your modem manual for a Dial
22    Command string that should work, and
23    type it into the Dial Command Box.
24 5) If all else fails, try the Alternate
25    Teleconnect Method (Page 41).
26
27
28 ”TeleWar will not Answer the Phone•
29
30 1) Is your modem powered & connected?
31 2) Check that the Modem Parameters are
32    correctly set.
33 3) Is your modem "AT" command set
34    compatable?
35 4) Consult your modem manual for an
36    Answer Command string that should
37    work, and type it into the Answer 
38    Command Box.
39 5) Try ATA command to force an
40    immediate answer. Set Receiving mode
41    after you hear the phone ring.
42 6) If all else fails, try the Alternate
43    Teleconnect Method (Page 41).

                  Page 45


1  Teleconnected, but the Game will not Work
2
3  1) Are both computers set to the same
4     baud rate?
5  2) Was a game previously started on one
6     or both of the computers when the
7     teleconnection was made?
8  3) Are both computers in the same Map,
9     For example, both in Desert Dunes?
10 4) Hangup and re-establish telephone
11    voice contact to verify settings,
12    then try again.
13
14
15 TeleConnect & Playing, then No Response
16
17 1) Are you still connected? Check the
18    Carrier Detect (CD) light on your
19    modem, if it has one.
20 2) Type in a message, or two, or three.
21    The chime may awaken your opponent.
22 3) If you or your opponent accessed the
23    the menus when the other was moving,
24    or were holding down the right mouse
25    button, messages might be scrambled.
26 4) If the SEND message line is echoed
27    back on your RECV message line (some
28    modems), then you are disconnected.
29 5) If you suspect that you have been
30    disconnected, then SAVE the game.
31    Choose the Disconnect menu option.
32    If the game is still active, and the
33    Cede/End Game menu is ghosted, select
34    the TeleConnect OFF mode (even if it
35    is currently selected) to force
36    activate the Cede/End Game option.
37
38
39 If you have Reached the End of your Rope
40 
41 Call our BBS at 1-(817) 244-4151 and ask
42 for help. We will do what we can, but
43 strategy and cunning are up to you!

